    {
        "content": "<p>I guess I can require compactness of the domain rather than completeness, which eliminates the rational examples at least</p>",
        "id": 554531210,
        "sender_full_name": "Snir Broshi",
        "timestamp": 1762659321
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Though that makes the statement pretty close to the extreme-value-theorem</p>",
        "id": 554531252,
        "sender_full_name": "Snir Broshi",
        "timestamp": 1762659417
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Maybe weakening the requirements of <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=ConvexOn.continuousOn_interior#doc\">docs#ConvexOn.continuousOn_interior</a> is the way to go, can they be weaker? Surely it can't be true only for reals</p>",
        "id": 554531294,
        "sender_full_name": "Snir Broshi",
        "timestamp": 1762659489
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>To me, it seems like you want something much closer to <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=IsCompact.exists_isMinOn#doc\">docs#IsCompact.exists_isMinOn</a>, but it's hard to tell without your application.</p>",
        "id": 554531348,
        "sender_full_name": "Bhavik Mehta",
        "timestamp": 1762659570
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah but that requires converting <code>ConvexOn</code> to <code>ContinuousOn</code> somehow</p>",
        "id": 554531421,
        "sender_full_name": "Snir Broshi",
        "timestamp": 1762659665
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>the application is not very relevant - I was trying to find a minimum of the gamma function, but since it's continuous for positive reals I don't need anything generic about convex functions and can just use the extreme-value-theorem directly (<a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/31409\">#31409</a>). I'm still curious about whether convexity can help finding a minimum</p>",
        "id": 554531500,
        "sender_full_name": "Snir Broshi",
        "timestamp": 1762659817
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>For a nonempty compact set K and a linear order L and an arbitrary function f : K -&gt; L, according to my intuition there should exists a point x in K such that the liminf of f(y) as y -&gt; x is globally minimized</p>",
        "id": 554533395,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1762662685
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>maybe if you're also convex that would let the liminf minimizer to be also minimizing the function value</p>",
        "id": 554533565,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1762662922
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>note that f doesn't need to be continuous (if I'm intuiting this correctly)</p>",
        "id": 554533584,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1762662947
    }
